<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-181-326 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 587 376</DOCID><JOURNAL>CSN  April 8 1991 n509 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Planning, not panic. (Viewpoint)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Orkand, Donald S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies that furnish systems integration and other informationservices to government agencies continuously publicize plans topursue commercial accounts in an effort to diversify, but thefederal market itself is highly diverse.andP;  The budgets of someagencies will be cut in the 1990s, but overall federalexpenditures are actually expected to increase.andP;  Government cannotbe termed a single market; there is enormous diversity even withindepartments; forward-thinking contractors will be able to offsetwell-expected budget cuts by finding other areas to apply theirskills within government.andP;  Those firms who move into thecommercial arena risk alienating their federal client base.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Strategic PlanningGovernment ContractsComputer Systems IntegratorsManagementUser NeedsDiversification.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>